We watch sports, in general, to admire the athletes' skill to play the
game.  We like to see the participants advance their skills from season
to season and generation to generation.  Each sport has a structure that
nurtures this concept and rewards skill and consistency much more than
luck.  It makes the outcomes fair and respectable, for the most part,
and provides a consistency to compare current players to ones from the
past.  NASCAR is flying in the face of this basic principle by using the
current points system.  They are leveling the playing field for the last
ten races to the point luck is becoming just as important as skill in
determining a season points champion.

I don't want to see a driver &quot;luck&quot; his way into being a points
champion, even if it is my favorite driver.  I want the championship to
be EARNED from a full season of racing by the BEST driver.  Not one that
can be 700+ points out of first and then miraculously string together a
luck based ten race run and win by a handful of points.  If that
driver/team had the necessary skill to EARN a championship he wouldn't
be 700+ points out of first after 26 races.  It's the equivalent of
running track and field events by giving mediocre runners huge head
starts over the more skilled ones.  Where's the entertainment in that?
